  <content>
    <title>Django Decision Tree</title>

    <summary>A comprehensive decision framework for Django development. Makes the right architectural decisions early in a Django project to prevent costly refactoring later. Covers framework selection, API framework choices, architecture patterns, database selection, deployment strategies, and third-party package evaluation with real-world examples and trade-off analysis.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Architectural decisions made at project inception compound over time. Choosing the wrong API framework, architecture pattern, or database early means either living with suboptimal solutions or expensive refactoring. A structured decision framework accelerates consensus and reduces post-hoc regret. Django's batteries-included philosophy can lead to over-engineering simple projects or under-architecting large ones. The decision tree helps teams right-size the framework, components, and patterns for their specific context: team experience, timeline, budget, and scale. Making the right choices early prevents costly refactoring later when business requirements change or technical debt accumulates.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new Django project and choosing between Django and alternatives (FastAPI, Flask, etc.).</item>
        <item>Selecting an API framework: Django REST Framework vs Django Ninja vs raw Django views.</item>
        <item>Evaluating architecture patterns for growing codebases — when to introduce a service layer or clean architecture.</item>
        <item>Choosing a database backend (PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite) based on project characteristics.</item>
        <item>Planning deployment strategy: PaaS vs VPS vs Kubernetes vs Serverless.</item>
        <item>Evaluating third-party packages for quality, maintenance, compatibility, and security.</item>
        <item>Code placement reviews — deciding where a new function belongs in the Django structure.</item>
        <item>Onboarding developers to project architecture and explaining design rationale.</item>
        <item>Architecture review of Django repo that has grown past 50 models.</item>
        <item>Third-party package vetting — comparing candidate Django packages by maintenance and compatibility.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>After spec sign-off with deployment chosen — re-running the full tree wastes cycles.</item>
        <item>When the choice is already constrained by infrastructure or team policy.</item>
        <item>Tiny scripts, ETL jobs, or single-page admin tools — Django is overkill.</item>
        <item>Greenfield projects where the bottleneck is product-market fit, not architecture.</item>
        <item>For a single feature inside an existing Django project — use code-placement guidance only.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="framework-selection">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Django when: building a web application (not CLI-only), needing an ORM, requiring an admin interface, managing user accounts and permissions, handling complex forms, or requiring server-side rendering. Consider FastAPI when: building API-only services, prioritizing async-first design, needing minimal dependencies, or the team prefers the FastAPI ecosystem.</statement>
        <rationale>Django's batteries-included approach makes full-featured web applications quick to prototype but adds overhead for minimal APIs. FastAPI excels at async-first, type-hinted APIs but requires manual setup for admin, auth, and ORM integration. Decision should be based on specific project requirements rather than general assumptions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Framework Selection Scenarios: Full-featured web app with admin = Django. API-only, high concurrency = FastAPI. Django + FastAPI-like API syntax = Django Ninja. Microservices, async-first = FastAPI. CMS with content editing = Django + Wagtail. Simple REST API = Django Ninja or FastAPI. When NOT to Use Django: Real-time only (WebSocket-heavy), extremely high concurrency, minimal API (less than 5 endpoints), no database needed, team has no Python experience. Should I Use Django checklist: Web application not CLI-only, need ORM, would benefit from admin, user accounts/permissions, complex forms, server-side rendering, value built-ins over components. Score 5+ = strong Django candidate, 3-4 = consider hybrid, 1-2 = consider FastAPI.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="api-framework-selection">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use DRF when: large existing DRF codebase, needing ViewSets for CRUD, requiring extensive serializer ecosystem, or prioritizing community resources. Use Django Ninja when: starting new project, prioritizing performance and type hints, preferring FastAPI-like DX, or needing auto-generated OpenAPI docs without extra packages.</statement>
        <rationale>DRF dominates market share and has mature third-party packages (drf-spectacular, rest-framework-simplejwt). Django Ninja is newer and lighter, with faster performance due to reduced serialization overhead and native async support. Choose based on project context, team experience, and specific requirements.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>API Framework Comparison: DRF maturity 13+ years vs Ninja 4+ years. Performance: DRF good, Ninja excellent. Type hints: DRF optional, Ninja native. Auto docs: DRF drf-spectacular, Ninja built-in. ViewSets: DRF native, Ninja manual. Ecosystem: DRF extensive, Ninja growing. Learning curve: DRF moderate, Ninja low. Async: DRF limited, Ninja native. Choose DRF when: large existing codebase, need ViewSets, complex nested serializers, browsable API important. Choose Ninja when: new project, performance priority, modern type hints, FastAPI-like DX. Choose raw views when: very simple API (2-3 endpoints), internal tool only, minimal serialization, zero dependencies.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="architecture-patterns">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Simple (Fat Models) for: small projects (less than 5 apps, less than 10 models), MVPs, prototypes, or 1-2 person teams. Use Service Layer for: medium projects (5-15 apps, 10-50 models), growing teams, multiple entry points, and moderate business logic. Use Clean Architecture / DDD for: large enterprise projects (greater than 15 apps, greater than 50 models), long-term maintenance, complex domain logic, or multiple bounded contexts.</statement>
        <rationale>Simple architecture reduces boilerplate for small projects but becomes unmaintainable as complexity grows. Service Layer keeps business logic testable and reusable. Clean Architecture enforces isolation for large teams. Selection depends on project scope, team size, and maintenance horizon.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Architecture Patterns: Simple (Fat Models) = less than 5 apps, less than 10 models, 1-2 developers, MVP/prototype. Service Layer = 5-15 apps, 10-50 models, 3-10 developers, complex business logic. Clean/DDD = greater than 15 apps, greater than 50 models, greater than 10 developers, complex domain. Microservices = domain-driven design with separate databases and async messaging.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="database-selection">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use PostgreSQL for: production environments, complex queries (CTEs, window functions), full-text search, JSON/JSONB fields, geographic data (PostGIS), or high write concurrency. Use SQLite for: development/testing, read-heavy workloads, single-server deployment, side projects/prototypes, or simplicity priority. Use MySQL for: existing MySQL infrastructure, team MySQL expertise, simple queries, or AWS RDS MySQL preference.</statement>
        <rationale>PostgreSQL provides advanced features and strong Django integration ideal for production. SQLite offers development simplicity and zero-configuration deployment. MySQL serves legacy infrastructure. Choose based on production requirements, team expertise, and operational constraints.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Database Selection: PostgreSQL (production, complex queries, full-text search, JSONB, PostGIS, high concurrency). SQLite (dev/test, read-heavy, single server, prototypes, simplicity). MySQL (existing infrastructure, team expertise, simple queries, AWS RDS). Development/testing always SQLite.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="deployment-options">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use PaaS (Render, Fly.io, Railway) for: simplicity, managed infrastructure, small teams, and rapid iteration. Use VPS (DigitalOcean, Hetzner) for: full control, cost optimization at scale, custom infrastructure, or team DevOps experience. Use Kubernetes for: horizontal scaling, zero-downtime deployments, high-availability, or microservices. Use Serverless for: highly variable traffic, cost optimization, stateless applications, or event-driven architecture.</statement>
        <rationale>PaaS trades control for simplicity and speed. VPS provides control and cost efficiency. Kubernetes handles scaling but adds complexity. Serverless optimizes for cost and scaling. Choose based on team expertise, scaling requirements, and operational overhead tolerance.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Deployment Options: Simplicity/managed = PaaS (Render, Fly.io, Railway). Full control = VPS (DigitalOcean, Hetzner). Enterprise/scaling = Kubernetes. Cost optimization = Serverless (Cloud Run, Lambda). Static sites + API = Vercel/Netlify + Django API. PaaS vs VPS: Simplicity (PaaS high, VPS low), Control (PaaS low, VPS high), Cost small (PaaS higher, VPS lower), Cost scale (PaaS higher, VPS lower), Maintenance (PaaS managed, VPS manual).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="code-placement">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use this decision tree: (1) Changes database? → services/. (2) External API call? → services/ or integrations/. (3) Pure function? → utils/. (4) HTTP handling? → views/. (5) Data structure? → models/. (6) Input validation? → serializers/. (7) Background task? → tasks/. (8) Reusable? → core/ or common/.</statement>
        <rationale>This hierarchy enforces testability (pure functions in utils), side effects isolation (services), and dependency direction (views depend on services, not vice versa). Correct dependencies prevent circular imports and improve code reusability.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="package-evaluation">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Before adding a package, verify: (1) Maintenance — commits within 6 months, (2) Compatibility — Django 5.x + Python 3.11+ support, (3) Community — GitHub stars, PyPI downloads, (4) Documentation — clear and complete, (5) Test coverage — CI passing, good coverage, (6) Security — no known vulnerabilities, (7) License — compatible with your project, (8) Necessity — cannot be done with Django built-ins.</statement>
        <rationale>Unmaintained, incompatible, or poorly documented packages create maintenance debt. Verify these signals before adding the dependency. Package Risk Assessment: Low (greater than 5k stars, active, documented), Medium (1-5k stars, maintained), High (less than 1k stars, no recent commits), Critical (abandoned, security issues).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Essential Packages 2025: API (django-rest-framework, django-ninja). Debug (django-debug-toolbar). Auth (django-allauth). CORS (django-cors-headers). Filtering (django-filter). Tasks (celery). Extensions (django-extensions). Environment (django-environ). Storage (django-storages).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="decision-examples">
      <p>Example 1: E-Commerce Platform - Team 5 developers, 6 months, 10k daily users. Decision: Django + DRF + Service Layer + PostgreSQL + PaaS. Outcome: MVP in 5 months, handling 15k users, easy to add features. Example 2: SaaS Analytics - Team 2 developers, 3 months, 5k users. Decision: Django + Ninja + Simple + PostgreSQL read replica + PaaS. Outcome: MVP in 2.5 months, excellent performance (less than 200ms), easy to maintain. Example 3: CMS - Team 4 developers, 4 months, 200 editors. Decision: Django + Wagtail + Service Layer + PostgreSQL + multi-tenancy. Outcome: On time, easy to add content types, clean separation. Example 4: Payment Microservice - Team 2 developers, 2 months, high reliability. Decision: Django + Ninja + Clean/DDD + PostgreSQL + Kubernetes. Outcome: Zero errors in 6 months, easy to add providers, excellent audit trail. Example 5: MVP Social App - Team 1 developer, 1 month, 100 beta users. Decision: Django + Ninja + Fat Models + SQLite + Fly.io free. Outcome: Live in 3 weeks, validated idea, easy to understand codebase. Decision Pattern Summary: context drives decisions, no universal best architecture, examples show trade-off analysis.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="version-compatibility">
      <p>Recommended versions 2025: Django 5.0+, Python 3.11+, PostgreSQL 14+, MySQL 8.0+, DRF 3.15+, Django Ninja 1.0+. Always check compatibility before adding packages.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-usage-tips">
      <p>When asking LLMs for architecture advice: provide specific project context (team size, timeline, budget, scale), state constraints clearly (must support PostgreSQL, deployed on Kubernetes), rank trade-off priorities (performance vs DX vs cost), include relevant code snippets, ask for concrete examples. Bad prompt example: What database should I use for Django? Good prompt example includes team size, data scale, query patterns, infrastructure constraints. Follow-up prompts: show minimal working example, what are common pitfalls, how would I migrate away, what monitoring needed. Effective prompting patterns: Decision (what you're deciding), Context (project type, team, constraints), Options (list of options), Trade-offs (prioritize performance/DX/maintenance/cost).</p>
    </section>

